Do you live in an area where the roads are salted often? If you do, you might want to invest in a car wash membership and wash it regularly to protect it from the salt. 

How Quick Quack can protect your car from the road salt:

‚ú® Paint protection: Our three-step paint sealant process adds a layer of carnauba wax and silicone to your paint that creates a barrier of protection against salt. It will also leave your car looking great.

‚ú® Advanced water filtration: Most car washes reuse water to lower their utility bills, which means they sometimes wash cars in water that contains traces of road salt. Quick Quack‚Äôs water reclamation system has a filtration process that removes soap, soil, oil and road salt.

Find out more ways that a visit to Quick Quack Car Wash can protect your car from road salt in the link in our stories.

At Quick Quack, we make it a habit to help others. And we loved helping Habitat for Humanity. On May 6, 2022, Team Members and Leaders from our Service Center volunteered in partnership with Rock The Block to help improve homes in the Oak Park Community. The Quick Quack Crew demolished old fences, weeded bamboo, shoveled garbage, poured concrete and established the foundation for new fencing. But most importantly, they helped strengthen a community! Our Mission is to Change Lives for the Better, on that day the lives of those who volunteered on the behalf of Quick Quack Car Wash had a life changing experience. Visit https://www.dontdrivedirty.com/jobs/ and see how you can be a part of this amazing team.

After over 20 years in Amarillo, TX, we opened a new location in late 2021. To kick off our Grand Opening, we held a Preview Fundraiser for the Mitchell Family. Jennifer Mitchell is raising her two granddaughters. Due to a health condition, she had to stop working, leaving her unable to pay for her medical bills and everyday expenses. With the help of the community, we raised and matched $4,000 to help Jennifer with her essential expenses. Thank you to United Way of Amarillo & Canyon for connecting us with the Mitchells, and to our community for supporting us.

We know that feeling when it just rained and you look at your car and think, "Wow, it looks pretty clean, maybe I don't need to wash it." But let us tell you, you should wash your car after the rain, and here are two reasons why.

The pressure and intensity of the rain is not strong enough to effectively remove all the dirt and grime from your car's surface. It may look cleaner, but trust us, there's still plenty of gunk on there.

Secondly, rainwater is often mixed with pollutants like dust and industrial emissions. This means that after a good rain, your car might be dirtier than before.

And the list doesn't stop there. 

Our blog, "Should I wash My Car After The Rain" (link in the bio), has more reasons to consider when washing your car after it rains - check it out.

.

This summer, we partnered with Make-A-Wish to make Elias' wish come true. Elias is a 12-year-old boy with a neurological condition that causes severe seizures. When @makeawishcanv approached Elias, he asked for his own backyard car wash. He loves playing in water and enjoys the fun soap and colors at Quick Quack. When our manufacturing team heard about Elias' wish, they stepped in and started conceptualizing the backyard car wash. This project is close to our hearts because our construction manager, Chad Terry, was a former Wish Kid. In addition, the family lives in Roseville, CA, right by our Quick Quack office.
After months of hard work, and with the help of @mybonney and @taylormorrisonsacramento, Elias' car wash came to life. It's the perfect place for the family to enjoy bubble parties in their backyard. Thank you to Make-A-Wish, our team and our partners for making this happen.

With Martin Luther King Jr. Day coming up on Monday. We thought we would give you some info on how cars played a part in fighting for equality in 1955. During the year long boycott of public transportation in Montgomery, AL, 325 privately owned cars picked up people in a carpool, so they wouldn't have to use public transportation. It was a success towards freedom and equality, partially due to cars, but mostly due to Martin Luther King Jr.'s leadership.

#AutoFactFriday Windshield wipers were first introduced by a woman in November of 1903. The genius behind this invention was Mary Anderson who noticed streetcar drivers had to open the windows of their cars when it rained in order to see, as a solution she invented a swinging arm device with a rubber blade that was operated by the driver from within the vehicle via a lever. By 1916, windshield wipers became standard equipment on all American cars.
